Let me analyze the project and plan the migration. Here's what I've found:

**Project details:**
- Next.js 16.2.0-canary.41 (App Router is well-established)
- React 19.1.0
- TypeScript (but current pages are JS)
- Has `@/*` path alias configured

**Pages Router files to migrate:**

1. `pages/_app.js` → `app/layout.tsx` (App Router root layout)
2. `pages/_document.js` → Migrate to `app/layout.tsx` (metadata API replaces `next/document`)
3. `pages/index.js` → `app/page.tsx` (Home page)
4. `pages/blog/index.js` → `app/blog/page.tsx` (Blog index)
5. `pages/blog/[id].js` → `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx` (Blog post)
6. `pages/404.js` → `app/not-found.tsx` (Custom 404)
7. `pages/_error.js` → `app/error.tsx` (Error page - uses App Router error pattern)
8. `pages/api/posts/index.js` → `app/api/posts/route.ts` (API route)
9. `pages/api/posts/[id].js` → `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts` (API route)

**Key App Router patterns to apply:**

1. **`pages/_app.js`** → Root layout (`app/layout.tsx`):
   - `<Component {...pageProps} />` becomes `{children}`
   - Wrap with `AppProvider` and header/footer
   - `next/head` → Next.js Metadata API or `<Head>` from `next/document` in layout

2. **`pages/_document.js`** → Merged into root layout:
   - `Html`, `Head`, `Main`, `NextScript` are implicit in App Router
   - HTML lang attribute → `<html lang="en">` in layout
   - Font preconnect → metadata or link tags
   - Title/description → `export const metadata` in layout

3. **`pages/index.js`** → `app/page.tsx`:
   - `getServerSideProps` → `fetch` in an async Server Component
   - `useRouter` for navigation → `<Link>` or `useRouter` from `next/navigation`
   - `Head` → Metadata API

4. **`pages/blog/index.js`** → `app/blog/page.tsx`:
   - `getStaticProps` with revalidate → `fetch` with `next: { revalidate: 60 }` in Server Component
   - `useRouter` for navigation → `<Link>` from `next/link`

5. **`pages/blog/[id].js`** → `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`:
   - `getStaticPaths` → `generateStaticParams`
   - `getStaticProps` → Server Component with direct `fetch`
   - `fallback: 'blocking'` → `dynamicParams: true`
   - `router.isFallback` → not needed, just check if data exists
   - `router.back()` → `useRouter().back()` from `next/navigation`

6. **`pages/404.js`** → `app/not-found.tsx`:
   - `useRouter` from `next/router` → `useRouter` from `next/navigation`
   - `Head` → Metadata API

7. **`pages/_error.js`** → `app/error.tsx`:
   - App Router uses `'use client'` error boundary with `error` and `reset` props
   - No more `getInitialProps`

8. **API routes** → Route Handlers:
   - `req, res` pattern → `NextRequest`, `NextResponse`
   - `req.method` checks → named exports (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`)
   - `res.status().json()` → `NextResponse.json()`

Let me create the task list and work through this systematically.

I need to:
1. Create the app directory structure
2. Convert all `.js` files to `.tsx`/`.ts` with proper types
3. Use App Router APIs
4. Delete the pages directory
5. Update next.config.ts if needed

Let me start creating the files. The App Router in Next.js 16 already reads from `app/` directory. I need to create all the files.

Let me plan the exact files:

**Files to create:**
- `app/layout.tsx` - Root layout (merges _app.js and _document.js)
- `app/page.tsx` - Home page
- `app/not-found.tsx` - 404 page
- `app/error.tsx` - Error boundary
- `app/blog/page.tsx` - Blog index
- `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx` - Blog post detail
- `app/api/posts/route.ts` - Posts API
- `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts` - Single post API
- `types/index.ts` - Shared types (or we can define them inline)

**Files to delete:**
- Everything in `pages/` directory
- Update `tsconfig.json` include pattern if needed (already includes `**/*.ts` and `**/*.tsx`)

Let me think about the component conversions carefully:

### 1. `app/layout.tsx` (merges _app.js + _document.js)

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';
import { AppProvider } from '@/components/AppProvider';
import '@/styles/globals.css';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: {
    default: 'My Blog',
    template: '%s - My Blog',
  },
  description: 'A complex blog application',
  icons: { icon: '/favicon.ico' },
};

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <head>
        <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
        <link 
          href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&display=swap" 
          rel="stylesheet" 
        />
      </head>
      <body>
        <AppProvider>
          <div className="app-container">
            <header>
              <h1>My Blog</h1>
              <nav>
                <Link href="/">Home</Link>
                <Link href="/blog">Blog</Link>
              </nav>
            </header>
            <main>
              {children}
            </main>
            <footer>
              <p>&copy; 2024 My Blog</p>
            </footer>
          </div>
        </AppProvider>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

Wait, Next.js in the App Router automatically wraps with `<html>` and `<body>`. But we can still render our own. Actually, we should just include the body content and let Next.js handle html/body OR we can use the `html` and `body` tags in the layout explicitly. In Next.js 16 with the App Router, the root layout does need to include `<html>` and `<body>` tags explicitly - that's the documented pattern.

### 2. `app/page.tsx` (Home page)

`getServerSideProps` → Server Component with inline fetch:
```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Home',
  description: 'Welcome to my blog homepage',
  openGraph: {
    title: 'Home - My Blog',
  },
};

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
}

export default async function HomePage() {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?_limit=5', {
    cache: 'no-store',
  });
  const posts: Post[] = await res.json();
  const timestamp = new Date().toISOString();

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome to My Blog</h1>
      <p>Server-side rendered at: {timestamp}</p>

      <h2>Recent Posts</h2>
      <ul>
        {posts.map(post => (
          <li key={post.id}>
            <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>{post.title}</Link>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <Link href="/blog">
        <button>View All Posts</button>
      </Link>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Wait, the original had `getServerSideProps` which fetches the user-agent from headers. In App Router, we can access headers via `headers()` from `next/headers`. Let me do that.

### 3. `app/blog/page.tsx`

`getStaticProps` with revalidate → Server Component with `next: { revalidate: 60 }`:
```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Blog',
  description: 'All blog posts',
};

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
}

export default async function BlogIndex() {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts', {
    next: { revalidate: 60 },
  });
  const posts: Post[] = await res.json();

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>All Blog Posts</h1>
      <div className="posts-grid">
        {posts.map(post => (
          <div key={post.id} className="post-card">
            <h2>
              <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>{post.title}</Link>
            </h2>
            <p>{post.body.substring(0, 100)}...</p>
            <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>
              <button>Read More</button>
            </Link>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 4. `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
}

interface Comment {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  body: string;
  email: string;
}

interface Props {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts');
  const posts: Post[] = await res.json();

  return posts.slice(0, 10).map(post => ({
    id: post.id.toString(),
  }));
}

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: Props): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { id } = await params;
  const res = await fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`);

  if (!res.ok) return { title: 'Post Not Found' };

  const post: Post = await res.json();

  return {
    title: post.title,
    description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    openGraph: {
      title: post.title,
      description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    },
  };
}

export default async function BlogPost({ params }: Props) {
  const { id } = await params;

  try {
    const [postRes, commentsRes] = await Promise.all([
      fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`, {
        next: { revalidate: 300 },
      }),
      fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}/comments`, {
        next: { revalidate: 300 },
      }),
    ]);

    if (!postRes.ok) notFound();

    const post: Post = await postRes.json();
    const comments: Comment[] = await commentsRes.json();

    return (
      <article>
        <Link href="/blog">← Back</Link>

        <h1>{post.title}</h1>
        <p>{post.body}</p>

        <h2>Comments ({comments.length})</h2>
        <div className="comments">
          {comments.map(comment => (
            <div key={comment.id} className="comment">
              <h3>{comment.name}</h3>
              <p>{comment.body}</p>
              <small>By: {comment.email}</small>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </article>
    );
  } catch {
    notFound();
  }
}
```

Note: I switched `router.back()` to `<Link href="/blog">Back</Link>` since we're in a Server Component and can just link.

Also, the original had `fallback: 'blocking'` which becomes `dynamicParams: true` (the default in App Router is already `true`, so we don't need to specify it). And `router.isFallback` is not needed since the component is a Server Component that awaits data.

### 5. `app/not-found.tsx`

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: '404 - Page Not Found',
  description: "The page you're looking for doesn't exist",
};

export default function NotFound() {
  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>404 - Page Not Found</h1>
      <p>The page you&apos;re looking for doesn&apos;t exist.</p>
      <Link href="/">
        <button>Go Back Home</button>
      </Link>
